<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18491126-159">
               <interp inst="t18491126-159" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18491126"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18491126-159" type="date" value="18491126"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18491126-159-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-159-18491126 t18491126-159-offence-1 t18491126-159-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>159. <persName id="def1-159-18491126" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-159-18491126" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-159-18491126" type="age" value="36"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-159-18491126" type="surname" value="STOKES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-159-18491126" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM STOKES</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18491126-159-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18491126-159-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18491126-159-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp>, feloniously forging and uttering an order for the payment of 125. with intent to defraud <persName id="t18491126-name-933" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-933" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-933" type="surname" value="RUSSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-933" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18491126-159-offence-1 t18491126-name-933"></join>Jonathan Russell</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-934" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-934" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-934" type="surname" value="MILLS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-934" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MILLS</persName>
                  </hi>. On Friday morning, 9th Nov., I was in Greenwich—I met the prisoner—he called to me and said, "<hi rend="italic">Jack</hi>, will you take this letter down to the Fisherman's Arms and bring back a blank?"—I agreed to do so—he gave me a letter; I took it to the Fishermans' Arms—I cannot read or write, but it was folded like a letter, like this—(<hi rend="italic">looking at a letter</hi>)—I saw Mr. Russell at the Fisherman's Arms, and a lady—I gave the letter to the lady and she gave it to Mr. Russell—I received a blank, which was open, from the lady—Mr. Russell was present—I took the blank to the prisoner—there was printing on it—the prisoner gave me a halfpenny and then left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Can you swear to me? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, by your face—you were dressed in a corduroy jacket and a hat—I have seen other persons working at Mr. Payne's warehouse in a corduroy jacket—I can swear it was you who gave me the halfpenny.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You heard him speak? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I saw him again on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184911260164"></xptr>
               <p>the Saturday in the station—he was with other men—I pointed him out immediately—when he spoke to me I saw his face very plainly—my name is John—I do not know how the prisoner knew my name.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-935" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-935" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-935" type="surname" value="RUSSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-935" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>JONATHAN RUSSELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the Fisherman's Arms, in Cold Bath-street, Greenwich, at the corner of Morden-street—on 9th Nov., a boy, who I should not know again, came between ten and twelve o'clock—Mrs. Russell sent a note of a declaration up-stairs—I came down and found the boy waiting—this is the note (<hi rend="italic">looking at it</hi>) that was sent up-stairs—I came down and tore the corner off a blank, and gave it to Mrs. Russell—the blanks are kept in a corner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Do not you tear them all off in the same way? <hi rend="italic">A</hi>, Yes; I do not swear to this—I gave four out that week, and this is one of them—I cannot speak to this being the same I gave Mrs. Russell—I have every reason to believe it is—she passed it over to the boy in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did you see the boy again? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the Wed<lb></lb>nesday following—the paper was brought to me the same day, about twelve o'clock, by John Flaxty, wrapped in a bit of paper—William Cornwell was present at the time—he is one of the visitors—I gave him the paper directly, and he said it was a counterfeit—David Anderson is a member of the com<lb></lb>pany, and there are about 400 others—in consequence of what Mr. Corn-well said, Flaxtey was taken that evening—I did not see the prisoner till he was brought into Court before the Magistrate—the paper was brought to me folded up as this is now.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-936" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-936" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-936" type="surname" value="FLAXTEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-936" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FLAXTEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in King's-street, Lewisham-road, and am a smith I have known the prisoner for some years—on 9th Nov. I saw him at the Coach and Horses public-house, about ten minutes before twelve o'clock—Mallett was there—the prisoner came in—we were saying we had had no breakfast, we should like to have a bit of bread and cheese—the prisoner said) "I have just turned a shilling job away; a woman has asked me to take a club paper to the Fisherman's Arms, but as I am a member I do not like to take it myself"—we spoke out directly and said, "I will go; I will go"—the prisoner went out of the house and came back directly with a note, and gave it to me—it was wrapped up in a piece of newspaper like this one—I took it, and gave the paper he gave me to Mr. Russell over the bar—Mr. Cornwell was there at the time—Mr. Russell opened it, looked at it, and gave it to Mr. Cornwell, and he said it was counterfeit—I said I knew nothing about it, but William Stokes, a member of the club, gave it me, and he was up at the Coach and Horses, he had better see him—I went back to the Coach and Horses—I saw the prisoner there, and told him it was a counterfeit—he ran out of the house directly, after this woman, as he said—he did not find her—I was taken into custody—I have always given this account of it, as near as I can remember.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-937" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-937" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-937" type="surname" value="CORNWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-937" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CORNWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, at 6, North Pole-place, Green<lb></lb>wich-road—I am a member of the United Brotherly Society—I am a steward and visitor—I was in the Fisherman's Arms on 9th Nov., about five minutes to twelve o'clock—I remember Flaxty coming in—he produced this order-Mr. Russell took it and gave it to me—this signature, "William Cornwell," is not my writing—I did not authorize any one to sign it for me—there is no other person of the same name belonging to the Society—five stewards sign on the back of the paper, and one on the front—I asked Flaxty where he got it—he said from the prisoner—no part of this is my writing—the prisoner came into the house shortly afterwards—I asked him how he came by that order—he told me a woman gave it him, with a red plaid shawl—I went with him up the bath and to the foot of Blackheath Hill—I found no woman in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184911260165"></xptr>
               <p>such a dress—he went down two streets, and came to me again, and said he could not find the woman—I said it was strange he could not find a woman who was waiting for the said 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I then went to the Coach and Horses and saw Flaxty—the prisoner said, "Billy to-day was not the day for your visiting"—I said, "No, to-morrow, hut to-day was my day if I thought proper to go to visit"—I left them in the Coach and Horses—I went to No. 12, Church-street, Lee—I did not find any person named John Jones there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner, Q.</hi> Did I not see you about ten o'clock in the morning? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; you did not ask me if you were fined for a steward.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-938" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-938" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-938" type="surname" value="WITHERSBY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-938" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WITHERSBY</persName>
                  </hi>. I reside in Bridge-street, Greenwich, and am secretary to the New United Brotherly Society. The prisoner has been a member of the society since 1840—he has been a steward and visitor—he can write a middling handwriting, and as visitor he would be acquainted with the laws of the society—there is no member of the society named John Jones, or James Wood—the names on this declaration are false—I believe it is the pri<lb></lb>soner's writing—this certificate of a surgeon named Dowling, and the signa<lb></lb>ture of Mr. Cornwell I believe to be the prisoner's writing—I believe the names on the back to be forged—I know the handwriting of the persons whose names are here—my brother's name is one—that is not my brother's writing, nor Mr. Gilbert's writing, nor the others.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you believe all the names at the back to be the prisoner's writing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I do—there ought to have been John Matthews, the sixth steward's name, but that is omitted.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> You have not seen me write for five or six years. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>, No, but I have got vouchers, by which he has claimed relief from the society, as lately as act. last, and have acted upon them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-939" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-939" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-939" type="surname" value="MONK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-939" type="given" value="WILLIAM ALFRED"></interp>WILLIAM ALFRED MONK</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Wellington-place, Lower-road, Deptford. I am one of the stewards of the society—I know the prisoner, and know his handwriting—I have seen him write—this declaration of sickness I believe to be his writing—the writing on the face of this order, and at the back of it, I believe to be his—my name is at the back of it—that is not my writing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-940" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-940" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-940" type="surname" value="CARPENTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-940" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CARPENTER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant, R</hi> 38). I apprehended the prisoner between ten and eleven o'clock on 9th Nov.—I told him he was charged with uttering a forged order for the payment of 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., with intend to defraud the United Brotherly Society—I cautioned him as to anything he might say, as I might give it in against him—he said it was a bad job, but he met a woman who asked him to take this order to the society's house for payment, and he told her as he was a member he did not like to take it—I searched his house, and in a box there 1 found part of the <hi rend="italic">Novel</hi> newspaper, which goes on to page 89, and this piece of newspaper handed to me by the witness is page 90—it was blotted with blue ink—this envelope is stained with blue ink—the order is written in blue ink, and I found some pens at the prisoner's which had been used with blue ink—the prisoner was asked if he could read or write, he aid he could not—Flaxty was asked, and he said he could, and he was asked to write his name, which he did—I have since that seen the prisoner write in the cell—I am quite sure I saw him write—he was down on his knees when I rent to fetch him out—he was writing on the back of an envelope—(<hi rend="italic">declaration read</hi>—" Sir,—Please to inform the stewards of the New United Brotherly Society that I am incapable of following my employ, and therefore declare on he funds of this society. John Jones, 12, Church-street")—(<hi rend="italic">certificate read</hi> "To the stewards of the New United Brotherly Society. I hereby certify hat James Wood continues ill of inflammation of the hand, and is using the roper means for his recovery. William Dowling.")—(<hi rend="italic">order read</hi>—" Mr.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184911260166"></xptr>
               <p>Russell,—Please to pay James Wood, or bearer 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., due this 9th Nov., 1849, William Cornwell."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491126-name-941" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-941" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-941" type="surname" value="RUSSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-name-941" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>JONATHAN RUSSELL</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I am treasurer of this society—if this had been a genuine order, I should have been bound to pay it—they leave money in my hands to pay these orders.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> Any one that takes a note like this could get it just the same as 1 could, if I was <hi rend="italic">on the box</hi>; I believe Cornwell to be the cause of it all; I never could do it myself; I was never brought up to it; I have a wife and five children. <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18491126-159-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-159-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-159-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 36.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <rs id="t18491126-159-punishment-143" type="punishmentDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18491126-159-punishment-143" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491126-159-punishment-143" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                        <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-159-18491126 t18491126-159-punishment-143"></join>Confined Nine Months</rs>.</hi>
               </p>
